I'll explain both the same-origin policy and DOM inline script processing, as they're closely related security concepts.

## Same-Origin Policy

The same-origin policy is a fundamental web security mechanism that restricts how documents or scripts from one origin can interact with resources from another origin.

### What Constitutes an Origin

An origin is defined by three components:
- **Protocol** (scheme): http, https
- **Domain** (host): example.com, subdomain.example.com
- **Port**: 80, 443, 8080, etc.

```javascript
// Same origin examples (assuming current page is https://example.com:443)
✅ https://example.com/page2        // Same origin
✅ https://example.com:443/api      // Same origin (default HTTPS port)

// Different origin examples
❌ http://example.com              // Different protocol
❌ https://subdomain.example.com   // Different subdomain
❌ https://example.com:8080        // Different port
❌ https://other-site.com          // Different domain
```

### What the Policy Restricts

```javascript
// Cross-origin restrictions apply to:

// 1. XMLHttpRequest and Fetch API
fetch('https://other-domain.com/api') // Blocked without CORS

// 2. DOM access between frames/windows
const popup = window.open('https://other-domain.com');
popup.document.body; // Blocked

// 3. Canvas pixel data from cross-origin images
const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
const img = new Image();
img.src = 'https://other-domain.com/image.jpg';
ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0);
ctx.getImageData(0, 0, 100, 100); // Blocked (canvas tainted)
```

### Exceptions and Workarounds

```html
<!-- Some elements can load cross-origin resources -->
<img src="https://other-domain.com/image.jpg">           <!-- Allowed -->
<script src="https://other-domain.com/script.js"></script> <!-- Allowed -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://other-domain.com/style.css"> <!-- Allowed -->

<!-- CORS headers allow controlled cross-origin access -->
<script>
fetch('https://api.other-domain.com/data', {
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json'
  }
})
// Works if server responds with:
// Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://your-domain.com
</script>
```

## DOM Inline Script Processing

The DOM processes inline scripts differently from external scripts, with important security implications.

### How Inline Scripts Are Processed

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <!-- Inline script in head -->
    <script>
        console.log('Head script executed immediately');
        // DOM not fully loaded yet
        document.getElementById('myDiv'); // Returns null
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="myDiv">Content</div>

    <!-- Inline script in body -->
    <script>
        console.log('Body script executed when encountered');
        // DOM elements above this script are available
        document.getElementById('myDiv'); // Returns the div element
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Execution Timing

```html
<script>
    // Inline scripts block HTML parsing
    console.log('1. Inline script starts');

    // This will delay the page rendering
    for(let i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {
        // Heavy computation
    }

    console.log('2. Inline script ends');
</script>

<div>This content waits for the script above to finish</div>

<script>
    // Each script block executes in order
    console.log('3. Second script block');
</script>
```

### Content Security Policy (CSP) and Inline Scripts

CSP affects how inline scripts are handled:

```html
<!-- Without CSP, inline scripts execute freely -->
<script>
    alert('This runs without CSP');
</script>

<!-- With strict CSP header: Content-Security-Policy: script-src 'self' -->
<!-- This would be blocked: -->
<script>
    alert('This is blocked by CSP');
</script>

<!-- Solutions for CSP: -->

<!-- 1. Use nonce -->
<script nonce="random-nonce-value">
    alert('This runs with matching nonce in CSP');
</script>

<!-- 2. Use hash -->
<script>
    alert('Specific content hashed in CSP');
</script>

<!-- 3. Use 'unsafe-inline' (not recommended) -->
<!-- CSP: script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' -->
```

### Dynamic Script Injection

```javascript
// Creating inline scripts dynamically
const script = document.createElement('script');

// Method 1: Set text content (inline script)
script.textContent = `
    console.log('Dynamically created inline script');
    window.myFunction = function() { return 'Hello'; };
`;

// Method 2: Set src attribute (external script)
script.src = 'https://example.com/external-script.js';

// Add to DOM to execute
document.head.appendChild(script);

// Note: Dynamically created inline scripts may be subject to CSP
```

### Security Considerations

```html
<!-- Dangerous: User input in inline scripts -->
<script>
    // Never do this - XSS vulnerability
    const userInput = "<?php echo $_GET['input']; ?>";
    document.write(userInput);
</script>

<!-- Safer approaches -->
<script>
    // Escape user data
    const userInput = <?php echo json_encode($_GET['input']); ?>;

    // Or use textContent instead of innerHTML
    document.getElementById('output').textContent = userInput;
</script>

<!-- Best: Separate data from code -->
<div id="user-data" data-value="<?php echo htmlspecialchars($_GET['input']); ?>"></div>
<script>
    const userData = document.getElementById('user-data').dataset.value;
    // Process safely
</script>
```

### Module Scripts vs Regular Scripts

```html
<!-- Regular inline script -->
<script>
    // Executes in global scope
    var globalVar = 'accessible everywhere';
    console.log(this === window); // true
</script>

<!-- Module inline script -->
<script type="module">
    // Executes in module scope
    const moduleVar = 'scoped to module';
    console.log(this === undefined); // true

    // Can use import/export
    import { someFunction } from './module.js';
</script>
```

The same-origin policy and inline script processing work together to provide security while enabling functionality. The same-origin policy prevents malicious cross-origin access, while proper inline script handling (especially with CSP) prevents code injection attacks.

